    {
      "step_id": "aa70ba8d",
      "step_index": 5,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "hERG blockers commonly present:\n1) **A cationic center** that can engage electrostatic interactions in the inner cavity.\n2) **Aromatic/hydrophobic groups** that \u03c0-stack / make hydrophobic contacts with key residues (notably aromatic residues in the cavity).\n3) **A linker length** that positions the cation relative to the aromatic system to fit the cavity geometry.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T20:03:22.503642+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "ee4ce184",
      "step_index": 6,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "How this molecule fits:\n- The **piperidinium cation** provides a persistent **positive charge**, increasing the chance of strong binding in the channel pore region.\n- The **phenothiazine-like fused aromatic system** provides a **large, planar hydrophobic surface** well-suited for the aromatic-rich hERG cavity.\n- The **~3-atom tether** from the aromatic N to the piperidinium (N\u2013CH2\u2013CH2\u2013CH*) is in the common range seen in many high-risk hERG pharmacophores (enough flexibility to adopt binding poses).\n- **Sulfur atoms** (in the ring and thioether) increase **polarizability** and hydrophobic character, which often strengthens nonspecific cavity binding.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T20:03:22.503663+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "da515660",
      "step_index": 7,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "## 3) MECHANISTIC BASIS (how it would block hERG)",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T20:03:22.503685+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "892ebe64",
      "step_index": 8,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "- hERG blockers typically bind in the **central cavity** accessible from the cytosolic side when the channel is open/inactivated.\n- The **cationic amine** can form **electrostatic interactions** and/or stabilize binding via ion\u2013dipole interactions.\n- The **planar polyaromatic core** can make **\u03c0\u2013\u03c0 / hydrophobic contacts** with aromatic residues lining the cavity (classically implicated residues include Tyr/Phe in the S6 region).\n- The **flexible side chain** allows the molecule to \u201cthread\u201d into the cavity: aromatic core anchors in a hydrophobic pocket while the cation sits at an energetically favorable position.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T20:03:22.503706+00:00"
    },
    {
